<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written submission to the Environmental Audit Committee's inquiry on Plastic Carrie Bags</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt">Written </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt">evidence submitted by Regain Polymers Limited</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In my capacity as both Purchasing Director of Regain Polymers Limited and Vice Chair of the British Plastics Federation Recycling Group, I make the following written submission to the Environmental Audit Committee’s inquiry on Plastic Bags.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.65pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In regard to the overall principle of a tax on the use of single use carrier bags, it is not my intent in either of my above capacities to comment on the principal of the use of taxation to create desirable outcomes, other than to point out that, as Newton’s 3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">rd</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> law of physics teaches us, every action tends to create an equal and opposite reaction. I wish instead to focus upon the supplementary proposal to incentivise the use of biodegradable plastic bags by exempting them from the tax.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.65pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The mechanical recycling of end of life plastics is well established and indeed many every day plastic articles are now routinely manufactured using 100% recycled plastic and the drive is on to encourage greater adoption of recycled content in manufactured plastic products in order to absorb the increasing volumes of end of life plastic being collected from both the domestic and commercial and industrial waste streams.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.65pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">For this process to continue, it remains imperative that the plastics manufacturing sectors both here in the UK and in our overseas markets retains confidence in the integrity of our plastics waste stream and its suitability as a feedstock for long term durable second life plastic products.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.65pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The danger that biodegradable plastic presents to existing markets is simple. Once it becomes recognised that degradable plastic is routinely present in the UK plastic waste stream, confidence in recycled plastic will evaporate and not only will we fail to find new markets for the plastics we so ardently wish to recycle but those markets that already exist will themselves disappear. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.65pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Far from biodegradable plastic bags being given an exemption to the proposed carrier bag tax, the use of any biodegradable plastics should be discouraged. Far better would be an exemption given to carrier bags that were themselves manufactured from recycled plastic or at least contained a statutory minimum level of recycled plastic.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.65pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Regain Polymers Limited employs over 100 people at its Castleford site and as one of the largest recycler of Rigid Plastics in the UK today recycles approximately 40,000 Te of rigid waste plastics per annum of which nearly 30,000 Te is obtained from the UK’s used plastic waste stream. The Castleford site manufactures high quality recycled polymer compounds formulated to meet demanding customer specifications spread across the automotive, horticultural, construction, packaging and general plastic moulding sectors both in the UK and overseas. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.65pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Our customer base relies heavily upon our ability to create uniformity and reliability from a very diverse stream of waste plastics and the products produced are expected to perform to the same level of longevity and structural integrity as those made from Virgin Polymer.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Dangers of Biodegradable Plastic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.65pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A typical, though by no means exhaustive, list of products currently manufactured using high levels of recycled plastics would be as follows:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Drainage piping</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Drainage chambers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Damp Proof Membrane</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Wheel Bins</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Coat hangers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Storage boxes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Pallets</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Ground stabilisation grids</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">All these articles are expected to be long term durable and retain their structural integrity.              Degradable content would therefore be highly inappropriate and would almost certainly result in product failure over the short rather than long term.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.65pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The end of life plastic waste stream is already highly complex, being made up of many different and largely incompatible polymer types. The sorting technology currently available already struggles to accurately separate these different polymers and there currently exists no reliable method of separating out degradable plastic as a separate stream. It is therefore inevitable, once degradable plastic becomes routinely present in the end of life plastic waste stream that it will become inexorably mixed with non degradable plastics therefore finding its way to mechanical recyclers who will have no way of excluding it from their products.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is not that biodegradable plastic cannot be mechanically recycled; rather the very problem is that it can. A recent report from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">EuPC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> suggests that as little as 2% inclusion of degradable material can cause serious quality issues within a recycled polymer.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Perhaps the greatest risk, however, will be the resultant change in perception of the reliability and structural integrity of recycled plastics on the part of those markets we wish to encourage in their use of recycled plastic.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">To summarise our concerns and in the context of  product liability considerations, who in their right mind would continue to specify the use of recycled polymer into a long term durable product once biodegradable plastics were routinely appearing in the UK’s waste plastic stream.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendatio</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ns: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In my capacity as both Purchasing Director of Regain Polymers and Vice Chair of the BPFRG I would recommend that, in their deliberations concerning the advisability of the imposition of a Tax on the use of single use Carrier Bags, the Environment Audit Committee reject any proposal to provide a tax exemption to bags made with biodegradable plastic on the grounds that increased use of degradable plastic will pose a very real and immediate risk to existing high volume markets for mechanically recycled polymers.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, should the Environment Audit Committee wish instead to promote increased use of recycled plastics into second life plastic products, I would suggest that consideration be given to allowing a tax exemption for carrier bags containing a statutory minimum percentage of recycled polymer. Moreover, this is established technology as the Supermarket chain J. Sainsbury will attest as they successfully marketed a fully recycled carrier bag as long ago as the mid 1990s. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Bernard Chase</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">25 November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>